    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1942-09-13T21:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1942-09-13T21:00:00-05:00" n="571"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d571">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">811.20 Defense (M)/9000: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in China</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Gauss</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Chungking</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1942-09-14T09:00:00+07:00"
                            >September 14, 1942—9 a.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received 8 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>1032. Department’s 736, August 15, 8 p.m. National Resources Commission is
                    becoming increasingly concerned that it will not be able to supply sufficient
                    quantities of wolfram at Kunming to load outgoing planes which took lot 670 tons
                    in August (624 tons of wolfram) and which may have space in September for 1000
                    tons and perhaps more in October. Director of NRC undertakes to provide wolfram
                    as rapidly as possible but desires that arrangement be made for shipment of tin
                    if wolfram in sufficient quantity is not available. There are now 1000 tons of
                    refined tin available at Kunming. Embassy has informed NRC that matter has been
                    referred to Metals Reserve. Embassy assumes that, if Metals Reserve agrees to
                    take tin, terms with regard to price, quality, etc., will be settled in
                    Washington and that authorization will be given for CNAC to transport tin to
                    Dinjan for $750 per ton as in the case of wolfram.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Gauss</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
